<paragraph blockId="22.[216,1203,1262,2544]" pageId="22" pageNumber="85">Stratigrapbic position. In base of oolitic limestone in the Kyncialyn Mudstone Member of the Merlewood Formation.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[216,1203,1262,2544]" box="[266,1077,2091,2131]" pageId="22" pageNumber="85">
Geographic distribution. 
<typeStatus box="[739,825,2091,2131]" pageId="22" pageNumber="85">Type</typeStatus>
locality only.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[216,1203,1262,2544]" box="[266,982,2137,2176]" pageId="22" pageNumber="85">Geological age. Middle or late Visean.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[216,1203,1262,2544]" pageId="22" pageNumber="85">
Etymology. Derived from the Latin 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yoo" authorityYear="1994" box="[911,1039,2184,2223]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pseudozygopleuridae" genus="Psfudozygopleura" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coenogastropoda incertae sedis" pageId="22" pageNumber="85" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[911,1039,2184,2223]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="85">gracilis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meaning slender, slim.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[216,1203,1262,2544]" pageId="22" pageNumber="85">Remarks. This is a very rare species. Two specimens recovered for this study are characterised by the presence of the typical pseudozygopleurid protoconch, tall smooth teleoconch whorls which are almost symmetrically arched, and a circular shape of aperture. There is no other form comparable to this species.</paragraph>
